canonical:
  title: 賀平定安南箋
  author: 李穡
  language: lzh
  text: 崇居貳極翼文德於誕敷參决萬機揚戎兵於克詰屬玆播告擧有懽忻竊以蕞爾昏迷敢行剽竊實人神之共怒而天地之不容宜整六師以施九伐風霆動盪皇威耀於荒陬日月貞明獷俗歸於美化匪伊示武惟以底寧恭惟仁篤好生義敦除暴致一方之再造期四海之永淸凡在見聞疇非蹈舞伏念叨逢盛際喜聽捷音職雖係於鯷岑阻參稱賀心切馳於鶴禁倍祝康寧
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 賀平定安南箋
  author: 李穡
  language: lzh
  text: 崇居貳極。翼文德於誕敷。參决萬機。揚戎兵於克詰。屬玆播告。擧有懽忻。竊以蕞爾昏迷。敢行剽竊。實人神之共怒。而天地之不容。宜整六師。以施九伐。風霆動盪。皇威耀於荒陬。日月貞明。獷俗歸於美化。匪伊示武。惟以底寧。恭惟仁篤好生。義敦除暴。致一方之再造。期四海之永淸。凡在見聞。疇非蹈舞。伏念叨逢盛際。喜聽捷音。職雖係於鯷岑。阻參稱賀。心切馳於鶴禁。倍祝康寧。
korean:
  title: 하 평정 안남 전
  author: 이색
  language: kor
  text: 이극(貳極 왕태자)의 높은 위(位)에 계시면서 크게 펴는 문덕(文德)을 도우시고, 만기(萬機)를 참결(參決)하사 필승(必勝)의 작전(作戰)을 수행하시오니, 이번 포고(布告)에 모두들 환성(歡聲)을 올리옵나이다.그윽이 생각하옵건대, 의리를 모르는 조그만 것들이 감히 표절(剽竊)을 행함은 실로 신인(神人)이 공노(共怒)하는 바요 천지간에 용납하지 못할 일이온지라, 마땅히 육군(六軍)을 정돈하여 구벌(九伐 정벌하는 아홉 가지 법)을 베풀 것이온데, 풍정(風霆)이 동탕(動盪)하여 황위(皇威)를 먼 변방에 빛내고 일월(日月)이 정명(貞明)하여 사나운 풍속이 아름다운 성화에 귀복(歸服)하오니, 이는 무력(武力)을 시위함이 아니요 오직 평정(平定)을 위함이로소이다. 공손히 생각하옵건대, 인(仁)은 호생(好生)에 돈독하고 의(義)는 제폭(除暴)만을 위주하오니, 일방(一方)의 재조(再造)를 이룸으로써 사해(四海)의 영원한 평화를 기약하게 되었는데 무릇 보고 듣는 자 뉘 아니 기뻐 춤추오리이까. 엎드려 생각하옵건대, 외람되이 성시(盛時)를 만나 반갑게 첩보(捷報)를 듣삽고, 구실이 비록 제잠(鯷岑)에 매어 칭하(稱賀)에 참예하지 못하오나, 마음은 학금(鶴禁)에 달려가 있사오며 곱절로 강녕(康寧)을 축원하옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0350_010_0350&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Memorial Letter Celebrating the Pacification of Annam
  author: Lee Sek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Crown Prince dwells in the second seat of power, assisting in the great unfolding of civil virtue, and with authority over the myriad affairs of state, executes strategies of assured victory. Thus through this proclamation, all raise their voices in jubilation.

    I humbly reflect: when petty creatures, ignorant of righteousness, dare commit such transgression, it stirs the shared wrath of gods and men alike, and heaven and earth cannot countenance it. Therefore it is fitting to marshal the six armies and deploy the nine forms of punishment. When wind and thunder shake the earth, the imperial majesty shines forth to the distant borderlands; when sun and moon hold their steady brilliance, fierce peoples submit to righteous transformation. This is not mere display of arms, but the foundation of peace itself.

    I respectfully consider: benevolence takes root in the love of life, and righteousness stands firm in the removal of tyranny. Through the rebirth of a single region, we secure lasting peace across all lands. How could any who witness and hear this not dance in celebration?

    Yet I reflect with deepest reverence: though fortune has graced me with this glorious age, and my heart rejoices at these tidings of victory, my position binds me to distant duties, preventing my voice from joining the chorus of congratulation. Still, my spirit flies to the forbidden palace itself, and doubly do I offer prayers for your eternal health and peace.
  footnotes:
    - The 'second seat of power' refers to the Crown Prince's position as heir apparent and regent.
    - The 'six armies' and 'nine forms of punishment' are classical references to comprehensive military organization and legitimate justice.
    - The 'forbidden palace' (鶴禁) is a metaphorical reference to the royal court, expressing the author's loyalty despite physical distance.
